.TH "bathstat" 1 "@BATH_DATE@" "BATH @BATH_VERSION@" "BATH Manual"

.SH NAME
bathstat \- summary statistics for a profile file


.SH SYNOPSIS
.B bathstat
[\fIoptions\fR]
.I hmmfile


.SH DESCRIPTION

.PP
The
.B bathstat
utility prints a tabular summary of statistics for each profile in
.IR hmmfile .

.PP
.I hmmfile
may be '\-' (a dash character), in which case profiles are read from
stdin rather than from a file.

.PP
The output columns are:

.TP
.B idx
The index of this profile, counting from 1.

.TP
.B name
The name of the profile.

.TP
.B accession
The optional accession of the profile, or "\-" if there is none.

.TP
.B nseq
The number of sequences the profile was estimated from.

.TP
.B eff_nseq
The effective number of sequences used after applying sequence
weighting (e.g., the default entropy-based effective sequence number
calculation).

.TP
.B M
The length of the model in consensus positions (match states).

.TP
.B relent
Mean relative entropy per match state, in bits. This is the expected
per-position score against true homologs, and reflects the
entropy-weighting target for default-built models.

.TP
.B info
Mean information content per match state, in bits.

.TP
.B "p relE"
Mean positional relative entropy, in bits. A more precise version of
.B relent
that accounts for insertion and deletion transition probabilities.

.TP
.B compKL
Kullback-Leibler divergence from the background frequency distribution
to the average composition of the profile's consensus match states,
in bits. High values indicate compositionally biased profiles, which
can slow the acceleration pipeline.


.SH OPTIONS

.TP
.B \-h
Help; print a brief reminder of command line usage and all available
options.


.SH SEE ALSO

.BR bathsearch (1),
.BR bathbuild (1),
.BR bathfetch (1),
.BR bathconvert (1)

.PP
For complete documentation, see the BATH repository:
https://github.com/TravisWheelerLab/BATH


